window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>1","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : HEAT TRANSFER","question":"The vacuum and silvered surfaces of a vacuum flask walls are to respectively","images":[],"options":{"A":"Minimize conduction and convection and prevent radiation","B":"prevent conduction and convection and minimize radiation","C":"prevent conduction and minimize convection and radiation","D":"minimize conduction and prevent conduction and radiation"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A vacuum flask, also known as a Thermos, has three main components that work together to reduce heat transfer:    1. Vacuum: The space between the inner and outer walls is evacuated, which minimizes conduction and convection. Since there are no molecules to conduct heat, this significantly reduces heat transfer.  2. Silvered surfaces: The inner and outer walls are coated with a thin layer of silver, which is a poor emitter of radiation. This minimizes radiation heat transfer.    By combining these features, a vacuum flask can effectively reduce heat transfer via conduction, convection, and radiation, keeping liquids at a consistent temperature for an extended period.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>2","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"RECTILINEAR ACCELERATION : VELOCITY-TIME GRAPH","question":"the magnitude of the acceleration of a moving object is equal to the","images":[],"options":{"A":"gradient of a displacement-time graph","B":"gradient of a velocity-time graph","C":"area below  force-time graph","D":"area below a velocity-time graph"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The magnitude of the acceleration of a moving object is equal to the gradient (slope) of the velocity-time graph. This is because acceleration is the rate of change of velocity, and the gradient of the velocity-time graph represents this rate of change.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>3","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"FLUID AT REST : PRESSURE IN FLUIDS","question":"In which of the following states is maximum pressure exerted on a person","images":[],"options":{"A":"Standing on two feet","B":"Standing on one foot","C":"Lying on the floor","D":"Kneeling on the floor"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When you stand on one foot, your body weight is concentrated on a smaller area, resulting in maximum pressure exerted on the foot. This is because pressure is force per unit area (P = F/A), and by reducing the area (standing on one foot instead of two), the pressure increases.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>4","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : THERMIONIC EMISSION~~STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : X-RAYS","question":"What are cathode rays?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Stream of electrons","B":"Beam of neutrons","C":"Beam of protons","D":"Stream of alpha particles"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Cathode rays are streams of electrons that are emitted from a cathode (a negatively charged electrode) in a vacuum tube, such as a cathode ray tube (CRT) or an electron gun. They are produced when a high voltage is applied between the cathode and an anode (a positively charged electrode), causing electrons to be accelerated and emitted from the cathode.    Cathode rays are used in various applications, including:    - Cathode ray tubes (CRTs) in older televisions and computer monitors  - Electron microscopes  - Electron beam lithography  - Vacuum tubes","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>5","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CAPACITANCE, ARRANGEMENT AND APPLICATION","question":"The capacitance of a parallel plate capacitor","images":[],"options":{"A":"decreases when the separation between the plates decreases","B":"increases when the potential difference between the plates is increased","C":"is greater without a dielectric between the plates than with a dielectric","D":"is greater with a dielectric between the plates than without a dielectric"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The capacitance of a parallel plate capacitor is greater with a dielectric between the plates than without a dielectric. This is because the dielectric material increases the capacitance by reducing the effective electric field between the plates and increasing the amount of charge that can be stored.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>6","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"RECTILINEAR ACCELERATION : VELOCITY-TIME GRAPH","question":"The diagram above illustrates the movement of a cyclist from P to R. The distance travelled is determined by the","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"area under QR","B":"area under PQR","C":"gradient of PQR","D":"gradient of QR"},"answer":"B","explanation":"By finding the area under the velocity-time graph, you can calculate the distance traveled by an object over a given period of time.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>7","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES~~LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"A ray of light travels from a less dense medium to a denser medium. How are the speed and frequency of the light affected? The speed","images":[],"options":{"A":"increases and the frequency increases","B":"decreases and the frequency decreases","C":"increases and the frequency remains the same","D":"decreases and the frequency remains the same"},"answer":"D","explanation":"When a ray of light travels from a less dense medium to a denser medium, the following changes occur:    - Speed: Decreases (due to the increased density of the medium)  - Frequency: Remains the same (frequency is a property of the light wave itself and is not affected by the change in medium)    As light passes from a less dense medium (e.g., air) to a denser medium (e.g., glass or water), it is refracted, or bent. This bending occurs because light travels at different speeds in different media. The speed of light decreases as it enters the denser medium, but its frequency remains constant.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>8","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CIRCUIT","question":"The function of a fuse in an electric circuit is to","images":[],"options":{"A":"break the circuit when the current exceeds a certain value","B":"save energy by reducing the voltage","C":"ensure that the current in the circuit exceeds a certain value","D":"save energy by reducing the current"},"answer":"A","explanation":"A fuse is a safety device designed to protect an electric circuit from excessive current, which can cause damage or fire. It is a weak link in the circuit that breaks (melts) when the current exceeds a predetermined value, interrupting the power supply and isolating the circuit. This prevents damage to the circuit, appliance, or device, and reduces the risk of electrical shock or fire.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>9","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"NEWTON\u2019S LAWS OF MOTION : FIRST LAW","question":"A body moves with a uniform velocity when the resultant force on it is","images":[],"options":{"A":"greater than the frictional force acting on it","B":"less than the frictional force acting on it","C":"equal to zero","D":"equal to unity"},"answer":"C","explanation":"When the resultant force on a body is zero, it means that the forces acting on the body are balanced, and there is no net force causing acceleration or deceleration. In this case, the body will maintain its uniform velocity, meaning it will continue moving at a constant speed in a straight line.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>10","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"NEWTON\u2019S LAWS OF MOTION : SECOND LAW~~NEWTON\u2019S LAWS OF MOTION : THIRD LAW","question":"The law of conservation of momentum is stated for closed and isolated system. What are the two conditions for a system to be closed and isolated?","images":[],"options":{"A":"No external force acts on the system and there is no change in mass of the system","B":"No external force acts on the system and there is a gain in mass","C":"No external force acts on the system and there is a loss in mass","D":"An external force acts on the system and there is no change in mass"},"answer":"A","explanation":"No external force acts on the system and there is no change in mass of the system.    A closed and isolated system has two conditions:    1. No external force acts on the system: This means that there are no external forces, such as friction, gravity, or thrust, acting on the system. The system is not interacting with the environment through forces.  2. No change in mass: This means that there is no mass entering or leaving the system. The total mass of the system remains constant.    When these two conditions are met, the system is considered closed and isolated, and the law of conservation of momentum applies. This means that the total momentum of the system remains constant over time, and momentum is conserved.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>11","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"MOTION : SIMPLE IDEAS OF CIRCULAR MOTION","question":"A stone of mass 200 g attached to a string is made to revolve in a horizontal circle of radius 1.5 m at a steady speed of 5 ms-1. Calculate the tension in the string at the bottom of the circle    (g = 10ms-2)","images":[],"options":{"A":"5.3 N","B":"3.3 N","C":"2.0 N","D":"1.3 N"},"answer":"B","explanation":"m = 200 g = 0.2 kg; r = 1.5 m; v = 5 ms-1    F = mv2r = 0.2 &#215; 521.5  \u2234 F = 3.3 N","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>12","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY~~ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"To convert milli-ammeter to an ammeter, it is necessary to connect a resistance of","images":[],"options":{"A":"low value in series with it","B":"high value in series with it","C":"low value in parallel with it","D":"high value in parallel with it"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A milli-ammeter is designed to measure small currents (in milliamperes). To convert it into an ammeter (which measures larger currents), you need to connect a shunt resistor (a resistor with low resistance) in parallel with the milli-ammeter.    The low-value resistor allows most of the current to bypass the milli-ammeter, enabling it to measure higher currents without being damaged.    Thus, a low-value resistor in parallel effectively converts a milli-ammeter to an ammeter.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>13","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : PLANE MIRROR","question":"An object is placed 1.5m from a plane mirror. How far is the image from the object?","images":[],"options":{"A":"3.0m","B":"1.3m","C":"1.0m","D":"0.3m"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Distance between image formed and mirror = Distance between object and mirror    Therefore, distance between image and object = 2 &#215; distance between object and mirror    Distance between image and object = 2 &#215; 1.5 = 3. 0 m","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>14","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"Chromatic aberration in lenses can be corrected by using a combination of","images":[],"options":{"A":"diverging and converging lenses","B":"an opaque material to cover the ruins of the lenses","C":"wide parallel beams on the lens' surface","D":"a thin convex lens"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The correct answer is: diverging and converging lenses.    Chromatic aberration is a common issue in lenses where different colors of light are focused at different points, resulting in a distorted image. This can be corrected by using a combination of diverging and converging lenses, known as an achromatic doublet or achromat.    An achromatic doublet consists of:    1. A converging lens (positive lens) made of a material with a high refractive index (e.g., glass)  2. A diverging lens (negative lens) made of a material with a low refractive index (e.g., flint glass)    The converging lens focuses the shorter wavelengths (violet and blue) while the diverging lens spreads out the longer wavelengths (red and orange), effectively canceling out the chromatic aberration.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>15","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"FLUID AT REST : EQUILIBRIUM OF BODIES: LAW OF FLOTATION","question":"A cube of wood size 10.0 cm floats vertically in water with 4.5 cm of its length submerged. Calculate the density of the wood.    (Density of water = 1 gcm-3)","images":[],"options":{"A":"0.450 gcm-3","B":"0.203 gcm-3","C":"0.090 gcm-3","D":"0.045 gcm-3"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Volume of cube = 10 cm \u00d7 10 cm \u00d7 10 cm = 1000 cm3    Volume of cube submerged = volume of water displaced = 10 cm \u00d7 10 cm \u00d7 45 cm = 450 cm3    Density of water = 1 gcm-3    Using Principle of floatation:    Weight of wood = weight of water displaced    \u21d2 Density of wood \u00d7 Volume of wood \u00d7 g = density of water \u00d7 volume of water displaced \u00d7 g (W = &#961;  \u00d7 V \u00d7 g)    \u21d2 Densitywood &#215; 1000 = 1 &#215; 450    \u21d2Densitywood = 4501000  \u2234 Densitywood = 0.450 gcm-3","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>16","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : TEMPERATURE AND ITS MEASUREMENT","question":"A temperature of 60 \u00b0C is equivalent to","images":[],"options":{"A":"25 \u00b0F","B":"50 \u00b0F","C":"108 \u00b0F","D":"140 \u00b0F"},"answer":"D","explanation":"100&#176;C &#8801; 212&#176;F    0&#176;C &#8801; 32&#176;F    60&#176;C &#8801; F    \u21d260 - 0100 - 0 = F - 32212 - 32  \u21d235 = F - 32180  \u21d2F - 32 = 3 &#215; 180 5 = 108  \u2234 F = 108 + 32 = 140&#176;F","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>17","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : X-RAYS","question":"All the following uses are practical applications of x-ray except","images":[],"options":{"A":"the treatment of tumours","B":"determining the depth of a mine","C":"dental operation","D":"detecting fracture in bones"},"answer":"B","explanation":"X-rays are not used to determine the depth of a mine. While X-rays can penetrate solid objects, they are not suitable for measuring the depth of large structures like mines.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>18","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : COULOMB\u2019S LAW","question":"Two isolated charged spheres each of magnitude + 1 &#215; 10-6 C are separated by a distance of 2.0 &#215; 10-1 m. Calculate the magnitude of the electrostatic force between them.    K =  1 4&#960;&#949;0  = 9 &#215; 109 Nm2C2","images":[],"options":{"A":"2.25 &#215; 10-1 N","B":"4.50 &#215; 10-1 N","C":"2.25 &#215; 101 N","D":"4.50 &#215; 101 N"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Using the formula:  F = Kq1q2r2 = Kq2r2  Where:  F = electrostatic force between the particles  q1 = q2 = q = magnitude of charge of each  r = distance of separation of the particles    F = 9 &#215; 109 &#215; (1 &#215; 10-6)2(2.0 &#215; 10-1)2  F = 2.25 &#215; 10-1 N","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>19","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CIRCUIT","question":"In the circuit above, which lamp causes the others to go off?","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"P","B":"Q","C":"R","D":"S"},"answer":"D","explanation":"When the lamp S is not connected, the circuit is open, causing other lamps go off.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>20","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"MOTION : SIMPLE IDEAS OF CIRCULAR MOTION","question":"A particle of mass 3.6 &#215; 10-6 kg revolving around the earth has a radial acceleration of 4.3 &#215; 107 ms-2. Calculate the centripetal force of the particle","images":[],"options":{"A":"6.25 &#215; 10-14 N","B":"1.55 &#215; 102 N","C":"1.00 &#215; 102 N","D":"2.00 &#215; 10-2 N"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Using F = ma:    F = 3.6 &#215; 10-6 &#215; 4.3 &#215; 107    \u2234 F = 1.55 &#215; 102 N","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>21","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"For a convex lens to form a real image, the distance between the object and the screen will be","images":[],"options":{"A":"equal to the focal length of the lens","B":"less than the focal length of the lens","C":"twice the focal length of the lens","D":"four times the focal length of the lens"},"answer":"C","explanation":"For a real image to be formed on a screen using a convex lens, the distance between the object and the lens must be at least equal to the focal length. Consequently, the distance between the object and the screen must be at least twice the focal length.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>22","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"SIMPLE A.C. CIRCUITS : PEAK AND R..M.S. VALUES~~SIMPLE A.C. CIRCUITS : SERIES CIRCUIT CONTAINING RESISTOR, INDUCTOR AND CAPACITOR","question":"The constant voltage source supplies a sinusoidal alternating emf. The voltage marked against the components are their peak values.  Determine the peak value of the applied emf","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"1 V","B":"4 V","C":"5 V","D":"11 V"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In an RLC circuit, the peak value of the applied emf is given by:    V = &radic;VR2 + (VL - VC)2&nbsp;    V = &radic;32 + (6 - 2)2&nbsp;    V = &radic;25&nbsp; = 5 V","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>23","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"SIMPLE A.C. CIRCUITS : PEAK AND R..M.S. VALUES","question":"A 2 \u03bcF capacitor is connected directly across a 150 Vrms, 60HZ A.C source. Calculate the rms value of the current","images":[],"options":{"A":"0.113 A","B":"0.160 A","C":"150 A","D":"1324 A"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Irms = VrmsXC  XC = 12&#960;fC = 12 &#215; &#960; &#215; 60 &#215; 2 &#215; 10-6  XC = 7.5398 &#215; 10-4\u03a9  Irms = VrmsXC = 1507.5398 &#215; 10-4  \u2234Irms = 0.113 A","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>24","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"PROJECTILE MOTION :","question":"A body of mass m is projected vertically upward with a velocity y. At what position will the potential energy be maximum?","images":[],"options":{"A":"y2  g","B":"2y2  g","C":"y2  2g","D":"y2  4g"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The potential energy (PE) of an object is given by:    PE = mgh    where m is the mass, g is the acceleration due to gravity, and h is the height above the ground.    As the body is projected upward, its potential energy increases as it gains height. The potential energy will be maximum when the body reaches its maximum height, which is when its velocity becomes zero (at the peak of its trajectory).    Using the equation for uniform motion:    v\u00b2 = vo\u00b2 + 2as    where v = 0 (at the maximum height), vo = y (initial velocity), a = -g (acceleration due to gravity), and s = h (height), we get:    0 = y\u00b2 - 2gh    Simplifying, we get:    h=y\u00b22g    So, the potential energy will be maximum at a height of y\u00b22g","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>25","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : ENERGY QUANTIZATION","question":"Light of energy 1.12 &#215; 10-18 J is incident on a metal of ejected electrons with maximum energy of 8.0 &#215; 10-19 J. Calculate the threshold frequency of the metal    [h = 6.626 &#215; 10-34 Js]","images":[],"options":{"A":"4.8 &#215; 1014 Hz","B":"1.2 &#215; 1015 Hz","C":"1. &#215; 1015 Hz","D":"2.8 &#215; 1015 Hz"},"answer":"A","explanation":"E = 1.12 &#215; 10-18 J; K.E = 8.0 &#215; 10-19 J; h = 6.626 &#215; 10-34 Js; fo = ?    E = W + K.E (where W = hfo)    \u21d2 E = hfo + K.E    \u21d2 hfo = E - K.E    \u21d2fo = E - K.Eh  \u21d2fo = 1.12 &#215; 10-18 - 8.0 &#215; 10-196.626 &#215; 10-34  \u2234 fo = 4.83 &#215; 1014 Hz","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>26","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"An object 2.0 cm high is placed at the radius of curvature of a concave mirror such that it is perpendicular to the principal axis of the mirror. Determine the height of the image.","images":[],"options":{"A":"0.5 cm","B":"1.0 cm","C":"1.5 cm","D":"2.0 cm"},"answer":"D","explanation":"An upright object placed at the centre of curvature, C, of a concave mirror has its image the same height as the object.    From the diagram above, the image, A'B', is of the same height as the object, AB.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>27","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"NEWTON\u2019S LAWS OF MOTION : SECOND LAW","question":"The diagram above illustrates two boxes P and Q of masses 27.3 kg and 6.2 kg respectively on a smooth horizontal surface. If a force of F of 150 N is applied to the combined forces, calculate the acceleration.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"4.5 ms_2","B":"33.7 ms-2","C":"70 ms-2","D":"150 ms-2"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Total mass = 27.3 + 6.2 = 33.5 kg    acceleration = Forcemass = 15033.5  \u2234 acceleration = 4.5 ms-2","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>28","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"NEWTON\u2019S LAWS OF MOTION : THIRD LAW","question":"A boy of mass 40 kg jumps off a stationary skateboard and moves horizontally with a speed of 1.5 ms-1 while the skateboard moves in the opposite direction with a speed of 20 ms-1. Calculate the mass of the skateboard.","images":[],"options":{"A":"60 kg","B":"40 kg","C":"3 kg","D":"2 kg"},"answer":"C","explanation":"m1 = 40 kg; m2 = ?; u1 = 0; u2 = 0;     v1 = 1.5 ms-1; v2 = -20 ms-1 (-ve since it moved in the opposite direction)    Using the principle of action = reaction (i.e. the law of conservation of momentum):    m1u1 + m2u2 = m1v1 + m2v2    \u21d2 40(0) + m2(0) = 40(1.5) + m2(-20)    \u21d2 0 = 60 - 20m2    \u21d2 20m2 = 60    \u2234m2=6020=3kg","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>29","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : COULOMB\u2019S LAW","question":"The depolarizing agent of the Leclanche cell is","images":[],"options":{"A":"powdered carbon","B":"manganese (IV) oxide","C":"carbon rod","D":"ammonium"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Leclanch\u00e9 cell is a battery that was invented and patented by the French scientist Georges Leclanch\u00e9 in 1866. The battery contains a conducting solution (electrolyte) of ammonium chloride, a cathode (positive terminal) of carbon, a depolarizer (oxidizer) of manganese dioxide, and an anode (negative terminal) of zinc (reductant) . Manganese dioxide (MnO2) is the oxidizing agent (depolarizer) in the Leclanch\u00e9 cell .","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>30","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"DERIVED QUANTITIES AND DIMENSIONAL ANALYSIS :","question":"Which of the following terms has different dimension from the other","images":[],"options":{"A":"Stress &#215; strain","B":"Stress/strain","C":"Pressure","D":"Torque"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Stress, pressure, and stress \u00d7 strain all have dimensions related to force and area, whereas torque has dimensions related to force and length (Newton-meters). This makes torque distinct from the other options in terms of dimensions.    Here's a brief summary:    - Stress: [ML-1T-2]  - Pressure: [ML-1T-2]  - Stress \u00d7 strain: [ML-1T-2] (since strain is dimensionless)  - Torque: [ML2T-2]","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>31","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CAPACITANCE, ARRANGEMENT AND APPLICATION","question":"A capacitor described as a mica capacitor has","images":[],"options":{"A":"both plates made of mica","B":"one of its plates made of mica","C":"a dielectric made of mica","D":"the same capacitance as that of mica"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Mica capacitors are a type of capacitor that uses mica, a group of natural minerals, as the dielectric material. Mica is used because of its high dielectric strength, which means it can withstand high voltages without breaking down. Mica capacitors are known for their high precision, stability, and low losses, making them suitable for high-frequency applications","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>32","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : EFFECTS OF HEAT ON MATTER~~HEAT ENERGY : THERMAL EXPANSION","question":"In which of the following devices is the thermal expansion considered a disadvantage","images":[],"options":{"A":"Fire alarm","B":"Thermostat","C":"Bimetallic thermometer","D":"Balance wheel of a watch"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In a balance wheel, thermal expansion would cause the wheel to expand and contract, affecting its precision and timekeeping accuracy. This is a disadvantage in a watch, where precise timekeeping is crucial.    In a watch's balance wheel, however, thermal expansion would be a disadvantage, as it would affect the precision of the timekeeping mechanism.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>33","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"The inside portion of a hollow metal sphere of diameter 20 cm is polished. The portion will therefore form a","images":[],"options":{"A":"concave mirror of focal length 5cm","B":"concave mirror of focal length 10cm","C":"convex mirror of focal length 5cm","D":"convex mirror of focal length 10cm"},"answer":"A","explanation":"When the inside of a hollow metal sphere is polished, the polished surface acts as the reflecting surface. Since this surface curves inward, it forms a concave mirror. The focal length of a concave mirror is equal to half of the radius of curvature (or half of the radius of the sphere).    Since the diameter of the sphere is 20 cm, the radius is 10 cm (half of the diameter).     Therefore, the focal length of the concave mirror is:    f=R2=102=5cm","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>34","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"PROJECTILE MOTION :","question":"Which of the following statements about a projectile is not correct?","images":[],"options":{"A":"A projectile is  two-dimensional motion","B":"A projectile is an object launched into air and allowed to move freely due to gravity","C":"The range of the projectile is independent of the acceleration due to gravity","D":"The time of flight is dependent on the acceleration due to gravity"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The range of a projectile is actually dependent on the acceleration due to gravity. The range is maximized when the angle of launch is 45 degrees, and it is affected by the acceleration due to gravity (g). The correct equation for the range (R) is:    R=u2sin2\u03b8g    where u is the initial velocity, \u03b8 is the angle of launch, and g is the acceleration due to gravity.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>35","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"FLUID AT REST : PRESSURE IN FLUIDS","question":"Atmospheric pressure decreases with an increase in altitude because","images":[],"options":{"A":"acceleration due to gravity increases with altitude","B":"temperature increases with altitude","C":"internal energy increases with altitude","D":"interaction among air molecules decreases due to less quantity of air"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Atmospheric pressure decreases with an increase in altitude because there are fewer air molecules above you, resulting in less weight pressing down on you. The atmosphere is made up of a vast number of air molecules, and the pressure we experience at the surface is due to the collective weight of these molecules.    As you go higher in altitude, the air density decreases, meaning there are fewer molecules per unit volume. This reduction in density leads to a decrease in atmospheric pressure.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>36","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : X-RAYS","question":"The main difference between x-rays and gamma rays is their","images":[],"options":{"A":"ionizing ability","B":"absorbing rate","C":"mode of propagation","D":"mode of production"},"answer":"D","explanation":"X-rays and gamma rays are both forms of ionizing radiation, but they differ in their origin:    - X-rays are produced by accelerating electrons outside the nucleus (e.g., in an X-ray tube).  - Gamma rays are produced by nuclear reactions or radioactive decay within the nucleus (e.g., from radioactive isotopes).","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>37","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES~~LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"The phenomenon used for explaining the formation of a rainbow in the sky is","images":[],"options":{"A":"interference","B":"refraction","C":"reflection","D":"dispersion"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The formation of a rainbow involves the dispersion of sunlight as it passes through water droplets in the atmosphere. Dispersion occurs because different colors (wavelengths) of light refract (bend) by different amounts when passing from one medium (air) into another (water).    As a result, white sunlight is split into its constituent colors, creating the spectrum seen in a rainbow. This process also involves refraction and total internal reflection within the droplets, but dispersion is the primary phenomenon responsible for the separation of colors.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>38","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"SIMPLE A.C. CIRCUITS : POWER","question":"Which of the following modes is the most economical method of transmitting electrical power over a long distance?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Alternating current at high voltage and low current","B":"Alternating current at low voltage and high current","C":"Direct current at high voltage and high current","D":"Direct current at low voltage and low current"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Transmitting electrical power over long distances is most economical when using alternating current (AC) at high voltage and low current. This is because power loss in transmission lines is primarily due to resistive losses, which are proportional to the square of the current (P = I2R).    By transmitting power at high voltage and low current, the current in the transmission lines is reduced, significantly minimizing power losses. High voltage transmission also allows for the use of thinner and less expensive cables.  This method is widely used in power grids to efficiently transmit electricity over long distances.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>39","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : RADIOACTIVITY","question":"The correct sequence of ionization power of alpha particle, gamma ray and beta particle respectively is:","images":[],"options":{"A":"low, medium, high","B":"high, medium, low","C":"medium, low, high","D":"high, low, medium"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The ionization power of radiation is related to their ability to interact with matter and ionize atoms and molecules. The sequence from highest to lowest ionization power is:    1. Alpha particles (high): Alpha particles are heavy and strongly interacting, causing significant ionization and damage to materials.  2. Beta particles (medium): Beta particles are lighter and less interacting than alpha particles, but still cause significant ionization.  3. Gamma rays (low): Gamma rays are high-energy electromagnetic radiation, but they are weakly interacting and cause relatively little ionization.    So, the correct sequence is: Alpha (high) > Beta (medium) > Gamma (low).","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>40","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CONDUCTION THROUGH MATERIALS","question":"Four pieces of constantan wire, marked E, F, G and H, each of length 1.0m, are at the same temperature. Their respective diameters are 1 mm, 2 mm, 6 mm and 10 mm. Which wire has the highest resistance?","images":[],"options":{"A":"E","B":"F","C":"G","D":"H"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Using the formula for resistivity:  R = &#961; lA  Where R = resistance, &#961;  = resistivity, A = Cross-sectional area, l = length of wire  Resistance is inversely proportional to area, and the larger the diameter, the larger the area.  The wire with the highest resistance will be that with the smallest area, and diameter by extension","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>41","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"TYPES OF WAVES : WAVE MOTION","question":"The maximum displacement of particles from equilibrium position in a wave motion is known as","images":[],"options":{"A":"wavelength","B":"amplitude","C":"frequency","D":"polarization"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Amplitude is the maximum displacement of particles from their equilibrium position in a wave motion. It is the maximum distance that the particles oscillate from their rest position.    Wavelength is the distance between two consecutive points on a wave that are in phase.    Frequency is the number of oscillations or cycles per second.    Polarization refers to the orientation of the wave's electric field vector.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>42","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : SPECIFIC HEAT CAPACITY","question":"A non-conducting vessel contains a liquid of mass 70.0 g at 25 \u00b0C. Another 70.0 g of the same liquid at 35 \u00b0C is quickly poured into the vessel. Determine the final temperature of the mixture","images":[],"options":{"A":"15 \u00b0C","B":"20 \u00b0C","C":"30 \u00b0C","D":"40 \u00b0C"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Let final temperature be &#952;    Heat lost by hot liquid = Heat gained by cooler liquid.    The masses of both liquids = 70g, their specific heat capacities are the same.    Using H = mc&#952;    70 &#215; c &#215; (35 - &#952;) = 70 &#215; c &#215; (&#952; - 25)    35 - &#952; = &#952; - 25    2&#952; = 35 + 25 = 60    \u2234&#952; = 602 = 30 \u00b0C","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>43","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : SHUNT AND MULTIPLIER","question":"A galvanometer of full-scale deflection 10mA has a resistance of 5 \u03a9. Calculate the shunt needed to convert it to measure a current of 2 A.","images":[],"options":{"A":"0.025 \u03a9","B":"0.050 \u03a9","C":"0.250 \u03a9","D":"0.500 \u03a9"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Given: Ig = 10mA = 0.010 A, Rg = 5 \u03a9, I = 2 A    (I - Ig)Rs = IgRg    Rs = IgRgI - Ig = 0.010 &#215; 52 - 0.010  Rs=0.051.99  \u2234 Rs = 0.025 \u03a9","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>44","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"MAGNETIC FIELD : MAGNETIZATION AND DEMAGNETIZATION","question":"In storing magnets, the keepers are used to","images":[],"options":{"A":"cancel the effect of the earth's magnetism","B":"reduce self-demagnetization","C":"protect the magnet from stray electric field","D":"increase the strength of the magnet"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Keepers are soft iron pieces placed across the poles of a magnet to:    - Reduce self-demagnetization: By providing a path for the magnetic field lines to flow, keepers prevent the magnet from losing its strength over time due to internal demagnetization.  - Preserve the magnetic field: Keepers help maintain the magnetic field by providing a low-reluctance path for the field lines.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>45","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"SOUND WAVES : SPEED OF SOUND","question":"Which of the following factors does not affect the speed of sound?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Loudness","B":"Wind direction","C":"Temperature","D":"Material medium"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Loudness is a measure of the intensity of sound, not its speed. The speed of sound is unaffected by the loudness or intensity of the sound wave.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>46","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFLECTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"A convex mirror is used as a driving mirror; however, a disadvantage in this regard is that the image","images":[],"options":{"A":"it produces is virtual","B":"it produces is real","C":"it is not as bright as we would like","D":"appears farther away from the driver"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Convex mirrors are used as rearview mirrors in vehicles because they provide a wider field of view and a more comprehensive view of the surroundings. However, a disadvantage is that the image appears smaller and farther away than it actually is, which can be a drawback for the driver.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>47","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : SPECIFIC HEAT CAPACITY~~HEAT ENERGY : SPECIFIC LATENT HEAT OF VAPORISATION","question":"The amount of heat energy that will be extracted when 0.02 kg of water vapor condenses to water at 970C is    [Specific heat of vaporization of water = 2.26 &#215; 106 J kg-1, Specific heat capacity of water = 4200 J kg-1 k-1","images":[],"options":{"A":"45,452 J","B":"45,200 J","C":"25,200 J","D":"252 J"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Total energy extracted = Energy extracted for change of state + Energy extracted for reduction in temperature    Energy extracted for change of state:    H1 = mL = 0.02 &#215; 2.26 &#215; 106    H1 = 45,200 J    Energy extracted for reduction of temperature:    H2 = mc\u2206&#952; = 0.02 &#215; 4200 &#215; (100 - 97)    H2 = 0.02 &#215; 4200 &#215; 3    H2 = 252 J    Total energy extracted = H1 + H2 = 45200 + 252 = 45,452 J","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>48","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : TEMPERATURE AND ITS MEASUREMENT","question":"Water is readily available, but it is not a thermometric liquid mainly because it","images":[],"options":{"A":"clings to glass","B":"does not expand uniformly","C":"boils at low temperature","D":"is colourless"},"answer":"B","explanation":"For a liquid to be used in a thermometer, it must have a uniform and predictable expansion with temperature changes. This ensures accurate and consistent temperature measurements.    Water does not expand uniformly with temperature, particularly around 4\u00b0C where it reaches maximum density and begins to expand upon further cooling or heating. This non-uniform expansion makes water unsuitable as a thermometric liquid.    While water clings to glass and is colorless, these factors are less critical compared to its non-uniform expansion. The boiling point is also not the primary reason why water is not used in thermometers.    Therefore, the main reason water is not a thermometric liquid is its lack of uniform expansion.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>49","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : BOILING POINT","question":"The constant temperature at which a liquid changes into gaseous state is known as","images":[],"options":{"A":"evaporation point","B":"melting point","C":"dew point","D":"boiling point"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The boiling point is the temperature at which a liquid changes state from a liquid to a gas (vapor) at standard atmospheric pressure. It is a constant temperature for a specific liquid.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2024>50","subject":"Physics","year":"2024","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : THERMAL EXPANSION","question":"The diagram above illustrates the graph for","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"the variation of a volume of a gas with increasing temperature","B":"expansion curve of mercury","C":"expansion curve of liquid oxygen","D":"anomalous expansion of water"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Anomalous expansion of water refers to the unusual behavior of water when it cools. Unlike most substances, which contract and become denser when cooled, water expands and becomes less dense as it cools below 4\u00b0C. This means that water reaches its maximum density at 4\u00b0C, and then expands as it freezes into ice.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"}];